SIMPLE: mean
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mean
<hw>Mean</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meant</conjf> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧nt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Meaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>menen</ets>,
AS. <ets>m⟦aemac⟧nan</ets> to recite, tell, intend, wish; akin to OS.
<ets>m⟦emac⟧nian</ets> to have in mind, mean, D. <ets>meenen</ets>, G.
<ets>meinen</ets>, OHG. <ets>meinan</ets>, Icel. <ets>meina</ets>, Sw.
<ets>mena</ets>, Dan. <ets>mene</ets>, and to E. <ets>mind</ets>.
⟦root⟧104. See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Moan</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To have in the mind, as a purpose, intention, etc.; to intend; to
purpose; to design; <as>as, what do you <ex>mean</ex> to
do?</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>mean</qex> ye by this service ?</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xii.
26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye thought evil against me; but God <qex>meant</qex> it unto
good.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. 1. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not a Spaniard⟦br⟧
To say that it is yours and not to <qex>mean</qex> it.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To signify; to indicate; to import; to
denote.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>mean</qex> these seven ewe lambs ?</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xxi. 29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go ye, and learn what that <qex>meaneth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
ix. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mean
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have a purpose or
intention.</def> <mark>[Rare, except in the phrase to mean well, or
ill.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mean
<hw>Mean</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Meaner</adjf>
<pr>(m⟦emac⟧n"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Meanest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mene</ets>, AS.
<ets>m⟦aemac⟧ne</ets> wicked; akin to <ets>m⟦amac⟧n</ets>, a., wicked,
n., wickedness, OS. <ets>m⟦emac⟧n</ets> wickedness, OHG.
<ets>mein</ets>, G. <ets>meineid</ets> perjury, Icel. <ets>mein</ets>
harm, hurt, and perh. to AS. <ets>gem⟦aemac⟧ne</ets> common, general, D.
<ets>gemeen</ets>, G. <ets>gemein</ets>, Goth.
<ets>gam⟦aacute⟧ins</ets>, and L. <ets>communis</ets>. The AS.
<ets>gem⟦aemac⟧ne</ets> prob. influenced the meaning.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Destitute of distinction or eminence; common; low;
vulgar; humble.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Of <xex>mean</xex> parentage.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mean</qex> man boweth down, and the great man humbleth
himself.</q> <rj><qau>Is. ii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wanting dignity of mind; low-minded; base; destitute
of honor; spiritless; <as>as, a <ex>mean</ex> motive</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can you imagine I so <qex>mean</qex> could prove,⟦br⟧
To save my life by changing of my love ?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of little value or account; worthy of little or no
regard; contemptible; despicable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Roman legions and great Caesar found⟦br⟧
Our fathers no <qex>mean</qex> foes.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of poor quality; <as>as, <ex>mean</ex>
fare</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Penurious; stingy; close-fisted; illiberal; <as>as,
<ex>mean</ex> hospitality</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Mean</xex> is sometimes used in the formation of
compounds, the sense of which is obvious without explanation; as,
<xex>mean</xex>born, <xex>mean</xex>-looking, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Base; ignoble; abject; beggarly; wretched;
degraded; degenerate; vulgar; vile; servile; menial; spiritless;
groveling; slavish; dishonorable; disgraceful; shameful; despicable;
contemptible; paltry; sordid. See <er>Base</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mean
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mene</ets>, OF.
<ets>meiien</ets>, F. <ets>moyen</ets>, fr. L. <ets>medianus</ets> that
is in the middle, fr. <ets>medius</ets>; akin to E. <ets>mid</ets>. See
<er>Mid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Occupying a middle position;
middle; being about midway between extremes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being of middle age and a <qex>mean</qex> stature.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir. P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Intermediate in excellence of any kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>According to the fittest style of lofty, <qex>mean</qex>, or
lowly.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Average; having an intermediate
value between two extremes, or between the several successive values of
a variable quantity during one cycle of variation; <as>as, <ex>mean</ex>
distance; <ex>mean</ex> motion; <ex>mean</ex> solar day.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mean distance</b></col> (of a planet from the sun)
<fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the average of the distances throughout one
revolution of the planet, equivalent to the semi-major axis of the
orbit.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean error</b></col> <fld>(Math. Phys.)</fld>,
<cd>the average error of a number of observations found by taking the
mean value of the positive and negative errors without regard to
sign.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mean-square error</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Error of the mean square</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Math.
Phys.)</fld>, <cd>the error the square of which is the mean of the
squares of all the errors; -- called also, <altname>mean square
deviation</altname>, <altname>mean error</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean
line</b></col>. <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Bisectrix</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean noon</b></col>, <cd>noon as
determined by mean time.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean proportional</b></col>
(between two numbers) <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>the square root of their
product.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean sun</b></col>, <cd>a fictitious sun
supposed to move uniformly in the equator so as to be on the meridian
each day at mean noon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean time</b></col>, <cd>time as
measured by an equable motion, as of a perfect clock, or as reckoned on
the supposition that all the days of the year are of a mean or uniform
length, in contradistinction from <xex>apparent</xex> time, or that
actually indicated by the sun, and from <xex>sidereal</xex> time, or
that measured by the stars.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mean
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is mean, or
intermediate, between two extremes of place, time, or number; the middle
point or place; middle rate or degree; mediocrity; medium; absence of
extremes or excess; moderation; measure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But to speak in a <qex>mean</qex>, the virtue of prosperity is
temperance; the virtue of adversity is fortitude.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>mean</qex> in all things.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The extremes we have mentioned, between which the wellinstracted
Christian holds the <qex>mean</qex>, are correlatives.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A quantity having an intermediate
value between several others, from which it is derived, and of which it
expresses the resultant value; usually, unless otherwise specified, it
is the simple average, formed by adding the quantities together and
dividing by their number, which is called an <stype>arithmetical
mean</stype>. A <stype>geometrical mean</stype> is the <it>n</it>th root
of the product of the <it>n</it> quantities being averaged.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That through which, or by the help of which, an end
is attained; something tending to an object desired; intermediate agency
or measure; necessary condition or coagent; instrument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their virtuous conversation was a <qex>mean</qex> to work the
conversion of the heathen to Christ.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You may be able, by this <qex>mean</qex>, to review your own
scientific acquirements.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Philosophical doubt is not an end, but a <qex>mean</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense the word is usually employed in the plural
form <xex>means</xex>, and often with a singular attribute or predicate,
as if a singular noun.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>this means</qex> he had them more at vantage.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What other <qex>means is</qex> left unto us.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Resources;
property, revenue, or the like, considered as the condition of easy
livelihood, or an instrumentality at command for effecting any purpose;
disposable force or substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>means</qex> are very slender, and your waste is
great.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A part, whether alto or tenor,
intermediate between the soprano and base; a middle part.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mean</qex> is drowned with your unruly base.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Meantime; meanwhile.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A mediator; a go-between.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wooeth her by <qex>means</qex> and by brokage.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>By all means</b></col>, <cd>certainly; without fail;
<as>as, go, <ex>by all means</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>By any
means</b></col>, <cd>in any way; possibly; at all.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If <qex>by any means</qex> I might attain to the resurrection of
the dead.</q> <rj><qau>Phil. iii. ll.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <mcol><col><b>By no means</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>By no
manner of means</b></col></mcol>, <cd>not at all; certainly not; not in
any degree.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wine on this side of the lake is <qex>by no means</qex> so
good as that on the other.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Meander</ent>⟦br⟧
